  "description": [
    "EXCLUSION ACT REVIEWED 81 DAVIS U S No Longer Is Asylum for Oppressed of World Says Labor Secretary v By HARRY WARD International News Sendee The American people have defi nitely rejected the doctrine that the United States is an asylum for the oppressed and the misfits of the old world Secretary of Labor Davis declared today in discussing the new Inmigration act The tendency of thought in the United States in the past few years has been gradually running toward a more restrictive policy in immi gration matters Davis said In the discussion in Congress of the Inmigration bill just enacted and the action of both the Senate and House upon amendments excluding the Japanese from those eligible for admission to the United States as Immigrants it was evidenced that we are more and more coming to realize the propriety of making this nation a homogeneous one We have discovered that certain racial characteristics lend themselves bet ter than others to assimilation with the stock ot the original founders of the Republic Yellow Race Barred The yellow race has by this lat est immigration act been placed en tirely in a class not as an inferior people but as"
